05184nam a22007095i 9780813573182DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2015004939  a97808135731827 a10.36019/97808135731822doi  a(DE-B1597)530188  a(OCoLC)945735923  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHV6250.4.H66bM49 2015 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a362.88086641 aMeyer, Doug, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aViolence against Queer People :bRace, Class, Gender, and the Persistence of Anti-LGBT Discrimination /cDoug Meyer. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. Introduction: Social Inequality and Violence against LGBT People -- t2. More than Homophobia: The Race, Class, and Gender Dynamics of Anti-LGBT Violence -- t3. “I’m Making Black People Look Bad”: The Racial Implications of Anti-Queer Violence -- t4. Gendered Views of Sexual Assault, Physical Violence, and Verbal Abuse -- t5. Race, Gender, and Perceptions of Violence as Homophobic -- t6. “Not That Big of a Deal”: Social Class Differences in Viewing Violence as Severe -- t7. The Home and the Street: Violence from Strangers and Family Members -- t8. Conclusion: Anti-Queer Violence and Multiple Systems of Oppression -- tAppendix: Methods -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aViolence against lesbians and gay men has increasingly captured media and scholarly attention. But these reports tend to focus on one segment of the LGBT community—white, middle class men—and largely ignore that part of the community that arguably suffers a larger share of the violence—racial minorities, the poor, and women. In Violence against Queer People, sociologist Doug Meyer offers the first investigation of anti-queer violence that focuses on the role played by race, class, and gender. Drawing on interviews with forty-seven victims of violence, Meyer shows that LGBT people encounter significantly different forms of violence—and perceive that violence quite differently—based on their race, class, and gender. His research highlights the extent to which other forms of discrimination—including racism and sexism—shape LGBT people’s experience of abuse. He reports, for instance, that lesbian and transgender women often described violent incidents in which a sexual or a misogynistic component was introduced, and that LGBT people of color sometimes weren’t sure if anti-queer violence was based solely on their sexuality or whether racism or sexism had also played a role. Meyer observes that given the many differences in how anti-queer violence is experienced, the present media focus on white, middle-class victims greatly oversimplifies and distorts the nature of anti-queer violence. In fact, attempts to reduce anti-queer violence that ignore race, class, and gender run the risk of helping only the most privileged gay subjects. Many feel that the struggle for gay rights has largely been accomplished and the tide of history has swung in favor of LGBT equality. Violence against Queer People, on the contrary, argues that the lives of many LGBT people—particularly the most vulnerable—have improved very little, if at all, over the past thirty years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGaysxViolence againstzUnited States. 0aHate crimeszUnited States. 0aSocial classeszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/97808135